This relation is an equivalence relation.
                    The equivalence classes are {a, d} and {b, c}

                c)  The relation is reflexive since there is a loop at each vertex.
                    It is symmetric since every edge has 2 vertices and pointing in the both direction.
                    It is not transitive (a, b) and (b, c) but not (a, c).


             Exercise

             Which of these collections of subsets are partitions of {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}

                a)  {1, 2}, {2, 3, 4}, {4, 5, 6}
                b)  {1}, {2, 3, 6}, { 4}, {5}
                c)  {2, 4, 6}, {1, 3, 5}
                d)  {1, 4, 5}, {2, 6}

             Solution

                a)  This is not a partition, since the sets are not pairwise disjoint. 2 and 4 appear in 2 of the sets.

                b)  This is a partition
                c)  This is a partition

                d)  This is not a partition, since element 3 is missing from the sets


             Exercise

             Which of these collections of subsets are partitions of {−3, −2, −1, 0, 1, 2, 3}

                a)  {−3, −1, 1, 3}, {−2, 0, 2}
                b)  {−3, −2, −1, 0}, {0, 1, 2, 3}
                c)  {−3, 3}, {−2, 2}, {−1, 1}, {0}
                d)  {−3, −2, 2, 3}, {−1, 1}

             Solution

                a)  This a partition, since it satisfies the definition
                b)  This is not a partition, since the subsets are not disjoint

                c)  This a partition, since it satisfies the definition
                d)  This is not a partition, since the union of the subsets leaves out 0














